In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on `Application` and work the same way. You can keep overriding them.

However, MAUI also adds a more granular **Window lifecycle** model. You can override these on your `Window` (or in `CreateWindow`):

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* app teardown */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI equivalent | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` | Per-window, not per-app |
| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` | Fires when backgrounded |
| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` | Fires when foregrounded |
| *(none)* | `Window.Destroying` | New — cleanup hook |

For platform-specific lifecycle events, you can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` (e.g., `OnActivityStateChanged` on Android, `WillEnterForeground` on iOS).

**TL;DR:** Your existing overrides still compile and work. Migrate to the `Window` events when you need per-window or platform-specific granularity.
